LAFIA- Mohammed Musa Dan’Azumi, the Chairman Nasarawa State Universal Basic Education Board (SUBEB) on Monday disclosed that the board has shortage of teachers in all primary schools across the state. The SUBEB Chairman stated this in an interviewed with newsmen shortly after he was screened by the state assembly for another tenure in office in Lafia, the state capital. He said since 2011, during the first tenure of the immediate past administration, over 5000 primary schools teachers had been retired from active service but new teachers have not been recruited in the state. HOW NIGERIAN MEN CAN NOW NATURALLY STOP PREMATURE EJACULATION, LOW SPERM COUNT AND OTHER MEN'S SEXUAL NEEDS. MADAM ALWAYS WANTS IT BIGGER, STRONGER AND LONG-LASTING!!! According to him, “We have shortage of teachers in our schools but we have told the governor about it and very soon governor will give us go ahead to recruit teachers to primary school.” “If we can have structures and we don’t have manpower, those structures are useless and is as if is a place where somebody can take his rest. We can have shade of trees as class, if we have teachers it will help than have structures without teachers.” Polytechnic Students Key Into Mass Housing Project In Nigeria NYSC Registers 854 Corp Members In Yobe Amid Strict COVID-19 Preventive Measures “We have shortage of teachers in our schools is our big challenge now since 2011 till now we have not recruit teachers again but we are preparing to recruit them massively, ” he said.